[2] Bangladesh vaccination activities
Date: 20 May 2007
Source: International Herald Tribune [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/05/20/africa/polio.php>

Bangladesh begins emergency polio vaccination campaign
----------------------
Bangladesh began immunizing 2 million children against polio Sunday
[20 May 2007] in an emergency vaccination drive in a southeastern
region close to Myanmar, officials said. The campaign follows
confirmation that a polio-infected child from Myanmar was brought to
the cities of Chittagong and Cox's Bazar for treatment in March [2007].
"The children will receive a 1st round of vaccinations on Sunday [20
May 2007] and the concluding 2nd round will take place on [1 Jul
2007]," a government health department official said. The drive is
taking place in the districts of Chittagong, Cox's Bazar and Bandarban.
Records at 2 Bangladesh hospitals, one in Chittagong and the other at
Cox's Bazar, revealed that a 2 1/2-year-old boy from Rakhine State in
Myanmar, had been treated there in March [2007]. Chittagong doctors
collected samples from the boy and sent them to the National Polio
Laboratory in Dhaka. By the time the laboratory had confirmed the
disease, the boy's guardians had transferred him to the Cox's Bazar
hospital and then had him released and taken back to Myanmar.
Fearing that the boy might have spread the virus during his stay,
Bangladeshi health officials ordered the emergency vaccination drive
in addition to an ongoing national campaign begun last year [2006].
Myanmar began its own vaccination campaign last week after 2
polio-infected children were detected in western Rakhine State, near
the Bangladeshi border. It was not immediately clear whether one of
those children was [the child treated in Bangladesh].
Polio, which mainly affects children under 5, can cause paralysis in
a matter of hours. Bangladesh and Myanmar declared themselves free of
the disease in 2000. But last year [2006], Dhaka started a campaign
to immunize all of the country's 24 million children after 17 cases
of a form of polio were detected in border areas.
