[In the last posting (Poliomyelitis - worldwide (03): Myanmar, RFI
20070510.1497) there were 2 cases of polio confirmed in Myanmar, both
from western Rhakine (see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/burma_pol_96.jpg>
for a good map of Myanmar). The above newswire mentions 7 cases as of
15 May 2007. Checking the polio eradication website, the most recent
report on cases in Myanmar is dated 15 May 2007, and there were only
2 cases reported with most recent date of onset 29 Mar 2007:
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/casecount.pdf>. One
suspects that the additional cases (? 5 additional cases) are still
pending laboratory confirmation. In the prior ProMED-mail posting
there was the following statement: "'The virus strain was found to be
type-1, the same as the one found in India. It is believed to have
migrated via Bangladesh,' he said."
Of note, according to a Bangladeshi newswire Narinjara:
<http://www.narinjara.com/details.asp?id=1269>, Bangladesh conducted
emergency vaccination activities on 20 May 2007 near the border with
Myanmar in response to the cases reported in Myanmar. In the 2nd
newswire above [2] there was mention that one of the cases from
Myanmar had been hospitalized in Chittagong and Cox's Bazar for
treatment in March 2007 and specimens collected then were found to be
positive for wild poliovirus (see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/bangladesh_pol96.jpg>
for a map of Bangladesh and location of Chittagong and Cox's Bazar) .
The newswire does mention that it is unclear if the polio case
treated in Bangladesh was the same as one of the 2 original reported
cases from Myanmar.
While Bangladesh is 'blaming' Myanmar, and Myanmar is 'blaming'
Bangladesh, the earlier ProMED-mail posting had information
suggesting the genetic analysis of the wild poliovirus isolate(s?) in
Myanmar were related to those circulating in India. Clarification of
the situation in both Myanmar and Bangladesh from knowledgeable
source(s) would be appreciated. - Mod.MPP]
